## 2ct Cushion Cut vs 2ct Round Diamond Ring

The two most common shapes at 2ct are round and cushion, and buyers frequently compare them before committing. The comparison is not simply aesthetic — there are structural price differences.

**Price at 2ct:** Round brilliant cuts command a premium over cushion cuts at equivalent quality because of the round's universally higher demand and its superior light return efficiency. A 2ct GIA F-VVS2 Ideal round brilliant from Blue Nile is typically $15,000–$18,000 — $1,000–$4,000 more than the equivalent cushion. The Pillow Premium versus princess is the cushion being more expensive; versus round, the cushion is cheaper.

**Visual character:** Round cuts produce perfectly symmetrical, rotationally uniform sparkle — every facet works equally in every direction. Cushion modified brilliants produce a slightly less perfectly symmetrical sparkle that is warmer and more varied at the facet level. From a distance, both appear brilliant and highly reflective. Close-up, the round has a more mechanically perfect appearance; the cushion has more personality.

**Face-up size:** At 2ct, the cushion's square proportions create a face-up area of approximately 64mm² (8mm × 8mm) versus a round's approximately 63mm² at 2ct (8.96mm diameter, ~63mm² circular area). They are essentially the same face-up size at 2ct — the round's circular outline and the cushion's square outline create different shape impressions but similar total area.

**Which to choose:** If you have a strong preference for one shape over the other, follow it. If you are genuinely undecided: the cushion is more distinctive (fewer people wear cushions than rounds), slightly less expensive, and particularly suited to vintage and halo settings. The round is more classic, more universally flattering in all settings, and slightly more liquid in the secondary market. For complete cushion vs round analysis, see the [cushion vs round diamond guide](/cushion-cut-vs-round-diamond).


